WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.668
Welcome! Today we're revising a very important topic: Heat and Its Effects.

2
00:00:06.668 --> 00:00:10.674
We'll cover the key concepts, the classic exam traps,

3
00:00:10.674 --> 00:00:15.133
and exactly how to phrase your answers to score full marks.

4
00:00:16.133 --> 00:00:19.983
First, the most important distinction in this whole topic.

5
00:00:19.983 --> 00:00:22.971
Heat is a form of energy, measured in joules.

6
00:00:22.971 --> 00:00:28.680
Temperature is a measure of how hot or cold something is, measured in degrees Celsius,

7
00:00:28.680 --> 00:00:31.933
using a thermometer. They are not the same thing!

8
00:00:32.933 --> 00:00:33.987
Here's the trap.

9
00:00:33.987 --> 00:00:39.062
Never write, the object has more temperature, or, the heat is thirty degrees.

10
00:00:39.062 --> 00:00:44.928
And remember: an object at a higher temperature does not always contain more heat energy.

11
00:00:44.928 --> 00:00:47.103
A cup of boiling water is hotter,

12
00:00:47.103 --> 00:00:51.255
but a warm swimming pool contains far more heat energy overall,

13
00:00:51.255 --> 00:00:53.166
because it is so much bigger.

14
00:00:54.166 --> 00:00:55.679
Now, the golden rule.

15
00:00:55.679 --> 00:01:01.227
Heat always flows from a hotter object or place, to a cooler object or place.

16
00:01:01.227 --> 00:01:05.478
The hotter object loses heat, so its temperature decreases.

17
00:01:05.478 --> 00:01:09.728
The cooler object gains heat, so its temperature increases.

18
00:01:09.728 --> 00:01:14.699
And heat keeps flowing until both objects reach the same temperature.

19
00:01:15.699 --> 00:01:19.089
Trap alert! There is no such thing as cold moving.

20
00:01:19.089 --> 00:01:21.937
Never write, the cold air entered the cup.

21
00:01:21.937 --> 00:01:27.157
Instead, write, heat from the hot water flowed to the cooler surrounding air.

22
00:01:27.157 --> 00:01:33.259
Memorise this answering formula: heat travels from the hotter object to the cooler object.

23
00:01:33.259 --> 00:01:37.259
The hotter object loses heat and its temperature decreases,

24
00:01:37.259 --> 00:01:41.666
while the cooler object gains heat and its temperature increases.

25
00:01:42.666 --> 00:01:47.926
Heat has three effects you must know. One: a change in temperature.

26
00:01:47.926 --> 00:01:54.599
Two: expansion and contraction. And three: a change of state. Let's look at each one.

27
00:01:55.599 --> 00:02:00.302
When matter gains heat, it expands, increasing in size and volume.

28
00:02:00.302 --> 00:02:05.789
When it loses heat, it contracts. This happens to solids, liquids, and gases.

29
00:02:05.789 --> 00:02:09.066
But here's the trap: the mass does not change!

30
00:02:09.066 --> 00:02:12.201
If a question asks about mass after heating,

31
00:02:12.201 --> 00:02:15.621
the answer is always: the mass remains the same.

32
00:02:16.621 --> 00:02:19.468
Expansion explains so many everyday things.

33
00:02:19.468 --> 00:02:21.918
Railway tracks and bridges have gaps,

34
00:02:21.918 --> 00:02:25.427
so the metal can expand on hot days without buckling.

35
00:02:25.427 --> 00:02:30.061
Overhead cables sag on hot days because they expand and become longer.

36
00:02:30.061 --> 00:02:35.424
Running hot water over a tight metal lid makes it expand, so it's easier to open.

37
00:02:35.424 --> 00:02:40.985
And the liquid in a thermometer rises because it gains heat and expands up the tube.

38
00:02:41.985 --> 00:02:45.014
Next, change of state, when heat is gained.

39
00:02:45.014 --> 00:02:50.790
Melting turns a solid into a liquid: ice melts into water at zero degrees Celsius.

40
00:02:50.790 --> 00:02:55.932
Boiling turns a liquid into a gas rapidly, and only at the boiling point,

41
00:02:55.932 --> 00:02:58.046
one hundred degrees for water.

42
00:02:58.046 --> 00:03:03.610
Evaporation also turns a liquid into a gas, but slowly, and at any temperature.

43
00:03:03.610 --> 00:03:06.709
That's why puddles dry up even on cool days.

44
00:03:07.709 --> 00:03:11.205
When heat is lost, the changes go the other way.

45
00:03:11.205 --> 00:03:17.394
Freezing turns a liquid into a solid: water freezes into ice at zero degrees Celsius.

46
00:03:17.394 --> 00:03:23.802
Condensation turns a gas into a liquid: water vapour touches a cold surface, loses heat,

47
00:03:23.802 --> 00:03:29.336
and forms water droplets. So remember: gain heat to melt, boil or evaporate.

48
00:03:29.336 --> 00:03:31.666
Lose heat to freeze or condense.

49
00:03:32.666 --> 00:03:37.329
Here's a classic question: why do water droplets form on a cold drink can?

50
00:03:37.329 --> 00:03:43.063
The model answer: water vapour in the surrounding air came into contact with the cooler out

51
00:03:43.063 --> 00:03:44.449
er surface of the can.

52
00:03:44.449 --> 00:03:49.616
The water vapour lost heat to the cold surface, and condensed into water droplets.

53
00:03:49.616 --> 00:03:54.026
And remember, the droplets come from the air, not from inside the can!

54
00:03:55.026 --> 00:04:01.004
Examiners love comparing boiling and evaporation. Boiling is fast; evaporation is slow.

55
00:04:01.004 --> 00:04:06.638
Boiling happens only at the boiling point; evaporation happens at any temperature.

56
00:04:06.638 --> 00:04:12.752
And boiling happens throughout the liquid, while evaporation happens only at the surface.

57
00:04:13.752 --> 00:04:16.730
Concept four: conductors and insulators.

58
00:04:16.730 --> 00:04:20.898
A good conductor of heat lets heat pass through quickly.

59
00:04:20.898 --> 00:04:24.917
That's metals, like copper, aluminium, iron and steel.

60
00:04:24.917 --> 00:04:31.615
A poor conductor, or insulator, lets heat pass through slowly, like plastic, wood, rubber,

61
00:04:31.615 --> 00:04:37.941
styrofoam, fabric, air, and water. The trap: an insulator never blocks or stops heat.

62
00:04:37.941 --> 00:04:39.579
It only slows it down.

63
00:04:39.579 --> 00:04:44.938
So write: heat enters the box slowly, keeping the drink cold for longer.

64
00:04:45.938 --> 00:04:47.573
Let's see them at work.

65
00:04:47.573 --> 00:04:53.260
A cooking pot's body is metal, so heat passes quickly from the fire to the food.

66
00:04:53.260 --> 00:04:59.375
The handle is plastic or wood, so heat travels slowly to our hand and doesn't burn us.

67
00:04:59.375 --> 00:05:03.711
Wool traps air, so body heat is lost slowly, keeping us warm.

68
00:05:03.711 --> 00:05:09.257
And a styrofoam cooler box lets heat in slowly, so the ice cream melts slowly.

69
00:05:09.257 --> 00:05:12.669
One special point: air is a very poor conductor,

70
00:05:12.669 --> 00:05:16.438
so materials that trap air make excellent insulators.

71
00:05:17.438 --> 00:05:20.176
Now, answering technique for Section B.

72
00:05:20.176 --> 00:05:23.898
Markers look for these keywords: gains or loses heat,

73
00:05:23.898 --> 00:05:29.094
heat flows from one object to another, temperature increases or decreases,

74
00:05:29.094 --> 00:05:35.063
expands or contracts, good or poor conductor of heat, and at a faster or slower rate.

75
00:05:35.063 --> 00:05:40.891
Follow four steps: identify which object is hotter. State the direction heat flows.

76
00:05:40.891 --> 00:05:45.104
State the effect. Then link back to what the question asked.

77
00:05:46.104 --> 00:05:52.144
Time to test yourself! Ali touched a metal spoon and a wooden spoon left in the same room.

78
00:05:52.144 --> 00:05:56.842
The metal spoon felt colder. Are the spoons at different temperatures?

79
00:05:56.842 --> 00:06:02.614
Pause the video and try. Ready? The answer is no! Both spoons are at room temperature.

80
00:06:02.614 --> 00:06:05.701
Metal is a better conductor of heat than wood,

81
00:06:05.701 --> 00:06:11.138
so it conducts heat away from Ali's hand at a faster rate, making it feel colder.

82
00:06:12.138 --> 00:06:16.713
Let's recap. Heat is energy; temperature is the degree of hotness.

83
00:06:16.713 --> 00:06:21.011
Heat flows from hotter to cooler until temperatures are equal.

84
00:06:21.011 --> 00:06:26.904
Gaining heat means temperature rises, things expand, and may melt, boil or evaporate.

85
00:06:26.904 --> 00:06:32.519
Losing heat means temperature falls, things contract, and may freeze or condense.

86
00:06:32.519 --> 00:06:34.807
Expansion changes size, not mass.

87
00:06:34.807 --> 00:06:40.283
Conductors transfer heat quickly, insulators slowly, and they never block heat.

88
00:06:40.283 --> 00:06:44.304
And finally, never write that cold moves. Only heat moves!

89
00:06:45.304 --> 00:06:46.496
You've got this!

90
00:06:46.496 --> 00:06:52.532
Remember the golden rule, practise the answering formula, and use those keywords.

91
00:06:52.532 --> 00:06:56.704
Good luck with your revision, and all the best for PSLE!
